  There&#039;s almost no one on the road at this hour, not before last call.  The stink of the high-powered oversized engine preceded the monster in hand with the massive sound system.  The thing raced past with a scream of pistons and someone&#039;s shout.
  Against moonlight a large handbag arced past and into the bare lot beyond.
  I shuffled over to the bag, if only to get a clue who to throw it back at later.  The bag had fallen on its side, a couple of items half out.  Someone else&#039;s past at my feet, a time machine that cut into the present, whirling without course or heading to shatter the curtain between then and now.  I scooped up the whole mess and finished the half-drunken shuffle back to a waiting bed.

The next morning I forgot about the bag, made it in early for once fueled by coffee and a few extra energy pills, and hated the day and its heat.
  By the time I got home, I&#039;d forgotten the details of everything during the last couple of beers the night before.  But there sat a woman&#039;s bag, scuffed and beaten past the point of still being fashionable, on the counter.
  I grabbed a beer from the fridge, and tipped the bag&#039;s contents onto the counter.  A smaller bag with two different sets of lingerie smelling of woman, smoke, and too many other hints.  A hardcase, padded inside, with some makeup and perfumes.  A charger for electronics.  A small case of compact discs, tracks written on sleeves behind, with titles in sharpie.  A pair of tiny sport headphones.  But no wallet, no purse, and nothing to identify the poor bitch that had to resort to smacking some guy bare-handed.
  Except...
